<?xml version="1.0"?>
<gpx xmlns="http://www.topografix.com/GPX/1/1" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" version="1.1" creator="AllTrails.com" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.topografix.com/GPX/1/1 http://www.topografix.com/GPX/1/1/gpx.xsd">
  <metadata>
    <name><![CDATA[The Sierra Madre Nature Trail]]></name>
    <desc><![CDATA[For the 16-year-old Boboy Francisco, climbing Mt. Mataba in 1969 is but a preview of a great many things his fondness of the Sierra Madre mountain range can get him. Roughly a decade after that, the UP Mountaineers (UPM) under his tutelage, reached the top of  Mt. Irid, then followed it up with explorations of the Angilo Mountains two years later. They then trekked Montalban to Infanta via Matulid River, inspiring future week-long efforts in the Sierra Madre like the seven-day trek from San Mariano - Palanan in 2011, as well as another from Mauban to General Nakar in 2019. The Sierra Madre has effortlessly endeared itself to the core of the UP Mountaineers' adventurous spirit. UPM first summitted Mt. Mingan in 1999, Mts. Danayag and Maaling-aling in 2007, and Mt. Oriod in 2010, yet each one a prelude to what its founders have been yearning for since 1977. 

And in the summer of 2019, UPM decided to proceed with linking the Sierra Madre mountain trails from Mauban in Quezon to Sta. Ana in Cagayan. Dubbed the Sierra Madre Nature Trail (SMNT), the multi-year project aims, not only to establish and map the longest thru-hike destination in the country, but to help in the conservation of Sierra Madre and the protection of its biodiversity and indigenous peoples. Approaches include comprehensive community mapping, capacity-building workshops, and local trail research. 

Of course, conserving our last great forest is not a one-man show. It entails collaboration and onboarding of all local indigenous peoples communities, the local government units, the Protected Area Management Boards, the Mountaineering Federation of the Philippines, other local stakeholders, national agencies like the DOT, DENR, and NCIP, the private sector, and the general public. UPM has consulted stakeholders across the board and has worked on supplementing the project's efforts, albeit remotely, throughout the pandemic years. Fact-finding visits and exploratory treks have recommenced this year to add to the multi-day trails already documented and confirmed by the project team and its partners in sections across the provinces of Quezon, Laguna, Nueva Ecija, Aurora, Nueva Viscaya, Quirino. Isabela and Cagayan. 

Everything said and done, the entirety of SMNT is still NOT OFFICIALLY OPEN for public use. It is also neither owned nor operated by the UP Mountaineers. Access to certain open sections remains the discretion of the local Certificate of Ancestral Domain Title (CADT) holders, the Protected Area Management Boards (PAMB), and/or government units. A Sierra Madre Trail Conservancy is in the project's pipeline but before we can go that far, much work still needs to be done to make sure that the communities are ready to take on the influx of tourists without compromising the integrity and biodiversity of the Sierra Madre Mountain Range.]]></desc>
    <link href="http://www.alltrails.com">
      <text>AllTrails, LLC</text>
    </link>
